{"root cause occurrence datetime": "2021-03-09 18:08:00", "root cause component": "Redis01", "root cause reason": "```json
{
  "root_cause_service": "Redis01",
  "confidence": 0.82,
  "reasoning": "Analysis of the dependency graph and telemetry data points to Redis01 as Patient Zero. Key indicators: (1) Redis01 shows astronomically high cumulative counters — total_commands_processed at ~5.02B, total_connections_received at ~32.09M, keyspace_hits at ~3.82B, and rdb_changes_since_last_save at ~1.11B — all significantly elevated compared to the healthy Redis02 peer (total_connections_received ~72.87M on Redis02 vs ~32.09M on Redis01 is suspicious in isolation, but rdb_changes_since_last_save on Redis01 is ~24% higher and total_commands_processed is ~26% higher, suggesting Redis01 is receiving a disproportionate and unsustainable command load). (2) Most critically, Redis01 shows extreme network saturation: NETPacketsIn at ~5.68B and NETPacketsOut at ~5.16B — orders of magnitude higher than any other service in the graph, including the IG gateway nodes (IG01: ~402M in / ~374M out; IG02: ~403M in / ~375M out). This indicates Redis01 is either under a flood of inbound traffic or is in a pathological loop. (3) Redis01's used_memory_peak is only ~50.4MB versus Redis02's ~95.7MB, which combined with Redis02 reporting a current used_memory of ~13.4MB, suggests Redis01 may have evicted memory or crashed its persistence layer under load rather than growing normally. (4) The Tomcat tier (Tomcat01–04) all show elevated JVM memory usage, high ProcessingTime on http-nio-8003, and high network throughput, consistent with requests backing up while waiting on a degraded cache layer. Tomcat01 is particularly impacted with ProcessingTime ~957M ms vs Tomcat02–04 at ~179–194M ms, suggesting Tomcat01 has the highest affinity to the Redis01 shard. (5) The MG (middleware gateway) nodes MG01 and MG02 are both red with high NoHeapMemory usage (MG02 at ~947MB NoHeap is abnormal — likely class/metaspace leak under retry storms), consistent with cascading retry amplification originating from Redis01 latency. (6) apache01 filesystem metrics appear nominal (healthy available space on all mounts), and the access logs show normal HTTP 200 responses via k6 load test traffic, indicating the web tier itself is not the origin. (7) MySQL01 and MySQL02 are green and stable, ruling out the database layer as the root cause. The failure propagation chain is: Redis01 (network flood / command saturation) → Tomcat cluster (cache misses or hung connections causing request processing time explosion) → MG01/MG02 (retry storms causing NoHeap memory pressure) → IG01/IG02 (elevated packet rates from upstream retries) → apache01 (alert fires as the frontend SLA degrades). The trigger is most likely a runaway k6 load test (evident from k6/0.29.0 user-agent in access logs across apache01, Tomcat03, Tomcat04) that overwhelmed Redis01's connection and command processing capacity, combined with a possible misconfiguration of Redis01's maxmemory-policy allowing unbounded command queuing.",
  "recommended_action": "Immediate: redis-cli -h redis01 -p 6379 CLIENT KILL ID <runaway_client_ids> && redis-cli -h redis01 -p 6379 CONFIG SET hz 100 && redis-cli -h redis01 -p 6379 CONFIG SET maxmemory-policy allkeys-lru; then throttle k6 load test traffic at the load balancer: iptables -I INPUT -p tcp --dport 6379 -m connlimit --connlimit-above 500 -j REJECT; monitor with: redis-cli -h redis01 -p 6379 INFO stats | grep -E 'total_commands|connected_clients|blocked_clients'; if Redis01 does not recover within 5 minutes, failover Redis01 traffic to Redis02 by updating the application connection string and restarting Tom"}
